With final_comp dataframe as of Oct 23, 2017

This version of analysis is with

  1. standardized total_answer_score as dv (named as ansScore_t)
  2. log transformed covairates (numUsers24, hasAAnswer24, Views24)

final_comp_working <- read.csv("../_data/final_comp_1018.csv")

## Standardized ViewCount
final_comp_working$ansScore_t <- (final_comp_working$total_answer_score - mean(final_comp_working$total_answer_score)) / sd(final_comp_working$total_answer_score)

## Log transformation of Covariates
final_comp_working$NumUsers24 <- log(final_comp_working$NumUsers24 + 1)
final_comp_working$Views24 <- log(final_comp_working$Views24 + 1)

Pre-analysis using non-matched data

Difference-in-means: outcome variable

final_comp_working %>%
    group_by(anyCO) %>%
    summarise(n_posts = n(),
            mean_ansScore = mean(ansScore_t),
            std_error = sd(ansScore_t) / sqrt(n_posts))

Examining the region of common support

labs <- paste("Getting any CO moderation?", c("Yes", "No"))
prs_df %>%
  mutate(anyCO = ifelse(anyCO == 1, labs[1], labs[2])) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = pr_score)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "white") +
  facet_wrap(~anyCO) +
  xlab("Probability of getting any CO moderation") +
  theme_bw()

Executing a matching algorithm

final_comp_working_nomiss <- final_comp_working %>%  # MatchIt does not allow missing values
  select(ansScore_t, anyCO, one_of(covar)) %>%
  na.omit()

mod_match <- matchit(anyCO ~ length_body + QAskerRep + ChangedTags + NumUsers24 + Views24 + Subscription,
                     method = "nearest", data = final_comp_working_nomiss)
dta_m <- match.data(mod_match)
dim(dta_m)
## [1] 916  14

Examining covariate balance in the matched sample

Well do three things to assess covariate balance in the matched sample:

  1. visual inspection
  2. t-tests of difference-in-means
  3. computation of the average absolute standardized difference (standardized imbalance)

Visual inspection

It is useful to plot the mean of each covariate against the estimated propensity score, separately by treatment status. If matching is done well, the treatment and control groups will have (near) identical means of each covariate at each value of the propensity score.

Below is an example using the four covariates in our model. Here I use a loess smoother to estimate the mean of each covariate, by treatment status, at each value of the propensity score.

fn_bal <- function(dta, variable) {
  dta$variable <- dta[, variable]
  dta$anyCO <- as.factor(dta$anyCO)
  support <- c(min(dta$variable), max(dta$variable))
  ggplot(dta, aes(x = distance, y = variable, color = anyCO)) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.2, size = 1.3) +
    geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = F) +
    xlab("Propensity score") +
    ylab(variable) +
    theme_bw() +
    ylim(support)
}

library(gridExtra)
## 
## Attaching package: 'gridExtra'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     combine
grid.arrange(
   fn_bal(dta_m, "length_body"),
   fn_bal(dta_m, "QAskerRep") + theme(legend.position = "none"),
   fn_bal(dta_m, "NumUsers24"),
   fn_bal(dta_m, "Views24") + theme(legend.position = "none"),
   nrow = 3, widths = c(1, 0.8)
)
## Warning: Removed 9 rows containing missing values (geom_smooth).
